JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS - INDIA (ANDHRA PRADESH) (08)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Japanese encephalitis - India (Andhra Pradesh) (06) 991130211045
[1
Date: Wed, 1 Dec 1999 12:14:09 -0500
From: Sneller, Vishnu-Priya <vbs6@cdc.gov>

In response to Mr. Merritt Clifton's statement on vaccination taboos in India:
I am appalled by [the statement that "Many Indians believe that
vaccination violates fundamental precepts of their religious beliefs
because they interpret it as ingesting an animal substance...This antipathy
toward vaccination explains the use of a homeopathic response to JE. No
matter how JE vaccines are made, the belief will be that they are animal
products, and their use will be resisted for that reason."
Many more Indians, than generally assumed in the Western world, ingest
animal substance in India and certainly when they reside abroad. As far as
I know there is no taboo in Hindu religion against vaccinations. I can
confidently state that religious taboos as far fetched as those indicated
in this message are practiced by a MINORITY in India. The rate of
childhood immunizations are high enough to negate the declaration in this
message.
Japanese encephalitis vaccine is not a universally recommended childhood
vaccination and there is no known curative drug(s) for encephalitis other
than clinical case management. So whether the person opts for homeopathy
or other traditional form of treatment, the ultimate result would be the
capacity of the patient to be able to overcome the neurological damage
caused by the encephalitis. I may be biased towards the allopathic case
management techniques available in a hospital setting that may enhance a
positive outcome. But, that again depends upon the hospital.
What might be more appropriate as a criticism is the lack of a systematic
approach to the issue; i.e., how was it decided that there was indeed an
outbreak? Was the illness meningitis or encephalitis? What was the
epidemic curve in time, geography, and demography? What were the organisms
that were ruled out as causative agents? How was Japanese encephalitis
confirmed? How was the association with pigs considered higher risk than
the association with mosquitoes? Were any steps taken to rule out
Malaysia's Nipah virus which started with a report of a Japanese
encephalitis outbreak in Feb 1999?
All these steps may have been undertaken by the Andhra Pradesh Health
Ministry but not reported by the media or picked up by the various
ProMED-mail contributors.
--
Vishnu-Priya Sneller
e-mail: vbs6@cdc.gov
[It might go without saying that we do not post messages on ProMED-mail
that might be considered offensive. Still, I will say it: We do not post
messages on ProMED-mail that might be considered offensive. Clearly, the
original message was incorrect. -Mod.CHC
