[3
Date: Thu, 02 Dec 1999 16:37:26 +0000
From: Madhur Rao <products@arzt.co.uk>

This is in reference to Merritt Clifton' s comments about religious beliefs
hampering the success of immunization programs in India. For one who
practised in Pune, (Maharashtra), India for over seven years, I never came
across anybody who refused immunizations on the grounds of religious
beliefs. I was practising in a cosmopolitan area where people from all
walks of life and religious denominations, including Jains, lived. As per
the 1991 census Jains constituted only 0.4% of India's total population
which today stands at 993,169,512 (Registrar General & Census Commissioner
of India). In Andhra Pradesh State, the state in question, there are 26,564
Jains out of a population of 66,304,854. This is only 0.04% of the
population and less than the total Jain population of the United States
(approximately 60,000).
In 1986/87 we ran a successful Polio Immunization Program with the Round
Table Club (a young men's service organisation akin to the Rotary and Lions
Clubs) where we immunized over 2000 children in the slum areas of Pune,
over a five month period (Pulse Immunization). During this period we never
came across a single parent who refused the immunization on the grounds
that the children were ' ingesting an animal substance'. Our coverage was
over 90% of the population in those areas. Nor did we have a problem with
BCG,DPT or Measles/MMR Immunizations (which are part of the Primary
Immunisation schedule) at our Well Baby Clinic. In fact I have had more
problems convincing members of Jehovah's Witnesses in Kenya (where I was
practising for 8 years) about the benefits of immunizations and need for
blood transfusions than I have ever had with any other group. So to talk
about the beliefs of a community which are are as Premchand B. Gada
(JAFNA/JAINA Education Committee) puts it 'in very low minority' and try
and extrapolate this to the beliefs of a vast majority of Indians would
seem a little unfair.
As regards the pigs, Merritt Clifton's assertion that these are 'street
pigs and a vital part of the garbage disposal system' maybe true to some
extent. However, we must remember that the Erukala community in Andhra
Pradesh earns a livelihood by rearing pigs and is protesting against the
State Government's drive to kill all the them. The failure, if any, of the
immunization programme in Andhra Pradesh probably stems more from what an
Indian Express (National Daily) correspondent described as 'when the
killer came calling this year, the administration of country was deep
asleep. By the time the Government woke up, Japanese Encephalitis had
spread across the State and had killed 180 children (as reported on
1/12/99). The logistics of covering the vast affected areas and the ability
of getting the vaccine to the State which costs about Rs.500 (Â£7) per dose
is only going to further hamper any progress in getting to grips with this
problem. The Orissa State Government 's incompetence during the recent
cyclone only goes to show that 'preventive measures' are not words that
state or national bureaucrats and politicians in India are familiar with.
Its always appears to be case of closing the stable after the horse has
bolted out.
--
Dr.Madhur Rao
Director of Medical Affairs
arzT Medical Systems Ltd.
Bewell House
Bewell Street
Hereford, HR4 0BA, England
